  "prompt": "Will USB 3.1 require a different front panel header than USB 3? Also, will computer case makers implement USB-C on front panels?",
  "response": "Let me break this down:\n\nUSB 3.1 uses the same 19-pin header as USB 3.0, so no different header is required. The pinout remains compatible.\n\nAs for front panel USB-C, many modern cases are already implementing USB-C on front panels, especially in mid to high-end gaming and workstation cases. However, adoption is still gradual, and motherboards need to support the internal USB-C header to enable this feature.\n\nSome cases will have:\n- Traditional USB-A 3.0 ports\n- USB-C 3.1 or 3.2 front panel ports\n- Some have both for maximum compatibility\n\nSo while not universal yet, front panel USB-C is becoming increasingly common in newer computer cases.",
